c discourse, national policies, and large-scale infrastructure projects, Moore reveals wartime elites as far more calculated in thought and action than previous scholarship allows. Moreover, Moore positions the wartime origins of technology deployment as an essential part of the country's national policy and identity, upending another predominant narrative-namely, that technology did not play a modernizing role in Japan until the "economic miracle" of the postwar years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aJapan wartime empire. 4aJapan wartime ideology. 4aJapanese bureaucrats. 4aJapanese engineers. 4aJapanese imperialism. 4aJapanese infrastructure projects. 4aTechnology. 4aWorld War II. 4aimperialism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804786690zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786690.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles